message.reasoning_content:
The user is asking me to respond to a survey about AI in education as if I were a primary or secondary school teacher from Croatia. I need to provide responses to 10 statements about AI in education.

Let me think about reasonable responses from the perspective of a teacher:

[TT4G35A]: "Artificial intelligence helps teachers write or improve lesson plans." - This is generally true. AI tools can help with brainstorming and drafting. I would say "Agree"

[TT4G35B]: "Artificial intelligence enables teachers to adapt learning material to different students' abilities." - AI can help personalize content and adapt materials. I would say "Agree"

[TT4G35C]: "Artificial intelligence assists teachers in supporting students individually." - AI can provide personalized feedback and support. I would say "Agree"

[TT4G35D]: "Artificial intelligence supports students with specific needs (e.g. multilingual learners, students with special education needs)." - AI has good potential here with translation, text-to-speech, etc. I would say "Agree"

[TT4G35E]: "Artificial intelligence helps teachers automate administrative tasks." - This is clearly true - grading, attendance, scheduling, etc. I would say "Strongly agree"

[TT4G35F]: "Artificial intelligence enables students to misrepresent others' work as their own." - This is a real concern with AI tools like ChatGPT. I would say "Agree" (acknowledging it's a risk)

[TT4G35G]: "Artificial intelligence makes recommendations that may not be appropriate or correct." - AI does make errors and inappropriate suggestions. I would say "Agree"

[TT4G35H]: "Artificial intelligence amplifies biases that reinforce students' misconceptions." - This is a known concern with AI systems trained on biased data. I would say "Agree"

[TT4G35I]: "Artificial intelligence jeopardises the privacy and security of student data." - Data privacy and security are real concerns. 

For the last two items, I need to consider what a realistic teacher would think. On data privacy, that's definitely a concern worth acknowledging - I'd say "Agree". For the final statement about unsuitable pedagogical approaches, I'm uncertain whether teachers would actually implement AI suggestions without critical review, so "I don't know" seems more honest than a definitive position either way.
